**Clinical Reasoning:**
Raised pCO₂ on arterial blood gas (ABG) indicates hypoventilation. In a motorcyclist with a high-energy trauma mechanism, multiple potential sources contribute to impaired ventilation — including tracheal or bronchial injury (commonly seen in MVAs), rib fractures leading to restricted chest expansion, pulmonary contusions impairing gas exchange, and diaphragmatic injury reducing ventilatory efficiency. These findings collectively point toward dysfunction of both upper airway/respiratory center integrity and structural components of the respiratory apparatus. Hence, the most comprehensive explanation aligns with combined impairment.

